**Feature: What is your use case for such a feature?**

When trying to make sure that there are absolutely no XSS holes in a highlighted string, in the dashboard a text node is made, that then is filled with the content of the highlighting.

See also the function used in the dashboard exactly (tsx, not jsx): 

```tsx
export default function StringHighlighter({ hit, path }: { hit: Hit, path: string }) {
  const value = get(hit._highlightResult, path) as { value: string };
  const str = value.value.replace(/<(\/)?ais-highlight-(\d+)>/g, '{{{$1ais-highlight-$2}}}');
  const div = document.createElement('div');
  div.appendChild(document.createTextNode(str));
  const __html = div.innerHTML
    .replace(/{{{ais-highlight-\d+}}}/g, '<em>')
    .replace(/{{{\/ais-highlight-\d+}}}/g, '</em>');

  return (
    <span
      className="string"
      dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html }}
    />
  );
}
```

The big difference between our `Highlighter` and this function is that we rely on React to do the escaping, while the solution in the dashboard will 

We will also need to test if this makes sense in benchmarking, and not make everything slower. 

**Feature: What is your proposed API entry? The new option to add? What is the behavior?**

```diff
//higlightTags.js
const timestamp = Date.now().toString();

export default {
-   highlightPreTag: `<ais-highlight-${timestamp}>`,
-   highlightPostTag: `</ais-highlight-${timestamp}>`,
+   highlightPreTag: `{{{ais-highlight-${timestamp}}}}`,
+   highlightPostTag: `{{{/ais-highlight-${timestamp}}}}`,
};
```

I tried this in a story, and it seems to still work.

